summary.seg: This manuscript is part of a mid-13th century Bible in Latin containing Jerome’s prologues to the books Job to Daniel.

The Vulgate edition of the Bible was re-translated from the original Hebrew and Greek by St. Jerome (c. 341 to 420) in the second half of the 4th century. As he completed his translations of each book, he recorded his observations and comments in an extensive correspondence with other scholars; these letters were subsequently collected and appended as prologues for those books where they survived.

The manuscript is not thought to have been made in Paris, because the text is markedly different from a standard Parisian Bible, but elsewhere in France or possibly in England. There are two main scribal hands. There are several corrections in the margins. Fol 1 and other leaves in the first quire are damaged.

msItem.title: Jerome, Prefaces and Prologues to Sapiential Books with argumenta and Prologues to Tobit, Judith and Esther
Interpretations of words in Job-Song of Songs, Ecclesiasticus, Wisdom, Tobit-Esther, Isaiah-Malachi
Jerome, Prologues to Prophetical books (Isaiah, Jeremiah, Hosea, Malachi), with argumenta.
Jerome, Prologue to Books of Twelve minor Prophets
Isaiah, Jeremiah, Lamentations, Baruch, Ezekiel, Daniel, the last three books with prologues and Daniel with argumentum.

layout.p: Double columns of 49 lines. Ruled in plummet, written below top line, catchwords (unusually extensive and written within ruled lines of text block).

decoNote.p: Three red and blue parted initials [3-6ll] flourished and filled with penwork in both colours for Job (fol. 7r), Judith (fol. 52v) and Jeremiah (fol. 98r); alternate red and blue initials [2-9 ll] with blue and red pen flourishing and infill in both colours for the other biblical books, some prologues and numbers of chapters. Simpler penwork motifs in blue and red respectively for other chapters, prologues and lesser text divisions; alternate red and blue initials for prologues (fols. 63r-65v) alternate red and blue capitals for running headers; one line red and blue paraph marks, occasionally flourished; one-line red and blue Roman numerals in margins for chapters; capitals highlighted in red.

binding.p: Twentieth century, native dyed, red Nigerian goatskin over pasteboards by Cambridge Colleges Conservation Consortium. Preserved 19th century covers of the previous binding, brown calfskin over pasteboards.

provenance.p: At Trinity Hall by 1830 when it was listed in Haenel as no 17 Hieronymi comm. In Job: membr.
